WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.560
Hello everyone, my name is George. I'm a data scientist at the Financial Times

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:14.560
based in London and today I'm gonna walk you through our current pipeline that we

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:20.559
developed using RStudio Connect and then try and compare that pipeline with the

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:26.760
previous one we had and see what we have changed and how we have improved. So

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:29.879
we're gonna start with a brief introduction to the Financial Times and

00:00:29.879 --> 00:00:35.160
the team. We're gonna then move on to describing what data science means for

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:40.599
the Financial Times and what types of problems we're trying to solve and then

00:00:40.599 --> 00:00:45.840
we're gonna have an overview of our new pipeline and the previous pipeline, all

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:50.759
of the technologies involved and a point-to-point comparison between the

00:00:50.759 --> 00:00:57.680
two. Finally we're gonna go through our agile practices and see how Connect and

00:00:57.680 --> 00:01:03.799
our new pipeline have helped. So the Financial Times, as you might know, is a

00:01:03.799 --> 00:01:10.919
newspaper. It was first published in 1888 in London, where we are still based, so

00:01:10.919 --> 00:01:15.360
the main offices are in London. The Financial Times is operating on a

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:21.519
subscription model, which means any of our users needs to have an active

00:01:21.519 --> 00:01:27.839
subscription, either a company or an individual. So in terms of data, we have

00:01:27.839 --> 00:01:31.720
all of the subscription data, both for individuals and companies, which is really

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:40.279
nice if you want to aggregate things or track events and users over time. We have

00:01:40.279 --> 00:01:45.160
behavioural and demographic data, as you would expect, and we track events both

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:53.360
from our site and our app. So all of that data allows us to do a lot of analysis

00:01:53.360 --> 00:01:58.279
and develop different data science models that we then provide to different

00:01:58.279 --> 00:02:04.000
teams within the company, so we have many different stakeholders from across the

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:10.320
business. So moving on to the team, currently there are six of us. Back in

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:15.919
2017, there were just two of us, so we have managed to triple in size over the

00:02:15.919 --> 00:02:22.080
past two and a half years, and we are now planning to double again over the next

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:30.160
couple of months. So the team is Adam, Cloudy, Grace, Ollie, Simon and me. It's

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:35.720
really interesting how with wide backgrounds we all have, though we all

00:02:35.839 --> 00:02:40.960
have one thing in common, which is none of us is a software developer, and as you

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:47.279
will see in the decisions and technology we're using, this has driven some of the

00:02:47.279 --> 00:02:50.960
decisions on what tools we use and how we use them and what the processes

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:56.800
within the team are. So data science in the FT, if we wanted to

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:01.479
summarise that into just a few points, we would end up with three

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:06.600
points. So the first one is that we are trying to create models that allow users

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:10.639
to become more engaged with the product we offer, either the on-set products or

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:16.160
the app, and we usually try to do that by adding more personalisation to the

00:03:16.160 --> 00:03:20.759
user journey, so either by promoting specific types of content or different

00:03:20.759 --> 00:03:26.880
products that the user might have not interacted with in the past. A second

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:32.320
point is that we try to always optimise and make all of the different

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:37.479
parts of our acquisition funnel to be better, so we get better at acquiring new

00:03:37.479 --> 00:03:43.479
subscriptions and maintaining those subscriptions, and finally we develop a

00:03:43.479 --> 00:03:50.199
set of different metrics to make sure that the health of the business

00:03:50.199 --> 00:03:56.720
looks good. So from things like RFE, which is our key engagement metric, which

00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:02.679
is based on recency, frequency and volume of reader activity, to LTV, which

00:04:02.679 --> 00:04:11.360
is our lifetime value calculation that we use across our user base. So on top of

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:15.839
those three goals we have developed a few different models, as you would expect,

00:04:15.839 --> 00:04:22.079
so things like next best action and topic recommendations, so we try to

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:28.160
identify products or things that the user hasn't done on-site or on the app

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:34.040
recently and we try to send them a reminder or just a promotion for that

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:40.440
particular product, and also in terms of recommendations we provide content,

00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:48.160
personalised content and personalised topics for users to interact with. We

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:54.920
make predictions for the volume of new subscriptions based on past

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:59.440
business performance, we have attribution modelling where we try to identify

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:04.720
marketing campaigns that are real drivers of acquisitions and growth for the

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:10.399
business and then use that knowledge to make better decisions for where to

00:05:10.399 --> 00:05:18.119
spend our marketing budget. We segment users in many various different levels

00:05:18.119 --> 00:05:26.480
and then we use those segments for analysis or for data science models.

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:34.119
Finally we have a set of models around identifying potential leads for B2B

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:41.160
contracts, so if we identify a user that is a decision maker or someone that is

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:46.559
coming from a specific company that we know used to have a contract with us or

00:05:46.559 --> 00:05:53.399
maybe has one and we want to grow that, we can then ask them to move on to a

00:05:53.399 --> 00:06:00.440
B2B account. So into our sprint cycle, as I said in the beginning we use agile

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:04.880
principles to some extent, so we split our time into week sprints, we have our

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:09.440
planning and prioritisation meetings a few months before the actual start of

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:14.519
the sprint where we define requirements and objectives and dependencies with

00:06:14.519 --> 00:06:19.559
other teams or specific data points. We involve all of the relevant stakeholders

00:06:19.559 --> 00:06:23.079
in that discussion to make sure that we are doing things that are relevant for

00:06:23.079 --> 00:06:27.320
the business. Then we have a kick-off meeting just before we start working on

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:32.760
the sprint where we have a more detailed discussion on exactly how we're going to

00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:38.200
do all of the objectives and how we're going to go about fulfilling all of the

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:42.679
requirements. We create cards for our dashboard and then make sure that all of

00:06:42.679 --> 00:06:47.880
the existing dependencies have been met. Then we hold daily stand-ups where we

00:06:47.880 --> 00:06:54.119
again meet with all of the relevant stakeholders, we show results from

00:06:54.119 --> 00:06:59.040
early analysis we have done, we ask for feedback, we make sure that we are going

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:03.600
in the right direction and then in the end of the sprint we have a retro where

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:08.279
we take note of things that went well, things that didn't go as well and next

00:07:08.279 --> 00:07:16.160
steps for future iterations on the same project. So now let's actually go and see

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:22.720
what the current and the old pipelines look like. So back in 2017 we decided we

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:29.040
wanted to create our own custom pipeline so we found a tool or a framework called

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:33.440
Luigi which is written in Python and it's a really nice tool if you want to

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:40.519
create a custom pipeline for any language really. So before that we used

00:07:40.519 --> 00:07:44.720
to have a big dependency with our data platforms team so anything we published

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:48.559
would go through their platform so we wanted to move away from that, that's why we

00:07:48.559 --> 00:07:55.679
decided to go with Luigi. So at that time the pipeline was hosted on AWS and Amazon

00:07:55.679 --> 00:08:02.720
services so all of the data was in Redshift and we would have to create a

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:08.959
separate SQL script for any query we were running against Redshift. We would

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:12.839
then have to create Docker containers where we would have all of the R

00:08:12.839 --> 00:08:18.000
scripts and so we load the data from Redshift, do any data wrangling, load the

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.600
model, execute the model within the Docker container and then send the data

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:29.720
back to Redshift and back it's in S3 and on top of that we would have Jenkins to

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:33.200
make sure that we schedule the jobs to run whenever we need we needed them to

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:38.599
and I think I forgot to mention so Luigi is written in Python and the way that

00:08:38.599 --> 00:08:42.960
Luigi works is you need to provide the dependencies and the order in which the

00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:48.799
steps need to run and we do that by providing a Python script. So as you can

00:08:48.799 --> 00:08:52.960
see there are a few different technologies, we used to write SQL, R and

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:58.520
Python so it was hard to extend, hard to maintain and really hard for new joiners

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:02.359
to get up to speed with but it was really successful until we started to

00:09:02.359 --> 00:09:08.840
grow as a team. So then we found out about our Studio Connect which is now at the

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:13.840
core of our pipeline. We also now moved all of our infrastructure into Google

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:18.080
which was not a decision of the data science team, it was a decision from the

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:22.200
data platforms team but again it proved to be successful and we're quite happy

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:27.559
with that as well. So now the data comes from BigQuery and then we go straight

00:09:27.559 --> 00:09:33.679
into our Studio Connect where we run any R script, we load any model,

00:09:33.679 --> 00:09:39.719
execute the model and then store the outputs in BigQuery and buckets in GCS.

00:09:39.719 --> 00:09:46.599
So as you can see here all of the code required is just in R so we can have

00:09:46.599 --> 00:09:51.440
interactions with BigQuery or the buckets with using the relevant packages

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:56.280
in R so it's really nice to maintain, really easy for someone that knows how

00:09:56.280 --> 00:10:02.159
to code in R to get up to speed with and we're quite happy with it until up to

00:10:02.159 --> 00:10:08.919
now. So if we want to compare the two pipelines, so we said that now we only

00:10:08.919 --> 00:10:12.599
have R whereas in the past we had three different languages so that's

00:10:12.599 --> 00:10:17.559
definitely a benefit. We removed a lot of the complexity involved which was not

00:10:17.559 --> 00:10:23.080
really necessary as it seems. We can now publish and schedule things in just a

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:27.679
few minutes whereas in the past it would take around a day and if you were

00:10:27.679 --> 00:10:34.320
a new joiner maybe a week. We can make the most out of Shiny dashboards and

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:41.039
Shiny apps and just deploy anything we want really easy and also there is great

00:10:41.039 --> 00:10:45.320
integration to our team's capabilities. As I said we're not software developers

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:51.760
so maintaining a pipeline that involves Docker and Luigi and interacting with

00:10:51.799 --> 00:10:56.799
AWS was much much harder than what we have now and as you will see also in the

00:10:56.799 --> 00:11:02.039
end, the current pipeline fits greatly with all of the agile processes we have.

00:11:02.039 --> 00:11:11.679
So now we can briefly go through what setting up a Studio Connect involves. So

00:11:11.679 --> 00:11:16.320
as I said we are using Google but it would be more or less the same process

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:22.440
if you are using Amazon or any other cloud provider. So for us it was just a

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:27.039
matter of going to the console, creating a new instance which can be a very small

00:11:27.039 --> 00:11:32.559
Linux server in the beginning and then you can directly SSH onto the server,

00:11:32.559 --> 00:11:36.919
install all of the basic requirements like a version of R, a version of Java

00:11:36.919 --> 00:11:42.320
and RStudio Connect itself. You can also create a server-wide data store if you

00:11:42.359 --> 00:11:49.919
want to allow for data to be loaded between different jobs or different

00:11:49.919 --> 00:11:55.640
runs of the same job. And finally you just need to configure buckets and

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:59.760
BigQuery, create the relevant credentials and then use those inside

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:05.760
RStudio Connect and that's it. So in the beginning it might have taken us a

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:09.679
couple of days to get everything configured and create the proper

00:12:09.679 --> 00:12:14.400
documentation. If we were to replicate the server now it would probably take

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:24.599
just a couple of hours. So finally moving back to our sprint cycle and how RStudio

00:12:24.599 --> 00:12:31.159
Connect and the new pipeline have made us better at working in an agile setting.

00:12:31.159 --> 00:12:37.719
So creating markdown reports and providing results from any early

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:42.000
analysis we do is really easy now. We can move between research and development to

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:48.039
deployment whenever we need to. We can deploy multiple versions of the same

00:12:48.039 --> 00:12:52.679
model. Again that's really really easy and on top of that we can create

00:12:52.679 --> 00:12:58.960
dashboards or alerts to make sure that all of the models that we have look fine

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:07.640
and there is no performance drop or any failure in the scheduled runs. So as an

00:13:08.119 --> 00:13:15.400
overview we went quickly through those. So we saw how RStudio Connect is now

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:20.840
part of our pipeline and how it has improved the way we do data science.

00:13:20.840 --> 00:13:28.200
We briefly described how we configured and set up our new pipeline using Google

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:36.559
infrastructure. We saw how the deploying and scheduling markdowns and

00:13:36.679 --> 00:13:42.479
dashboards have made us better in working in an agile setting and finally

00:13:42.479 --> 00:13:48.919
how this also allows us to make sure that stakeholders are engaged and we can

00:13:48.919 --> 00:13:55.520
welcome feedback throughout the sprint cycle. So that was it for me.

00:13:55.520 --> 00:14:02.840
Just a reminder we're also hiring and as I said we're trying to double in

00:14:02.840 --> 00:14:06.760
size. I'm not sure how relevant this is because most positions are going to be

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:11.919
in London but feel free to follow the link and contact either the team or me

00:14:11.919 --> 00:14:15.760
directly. Thank you very much.

00:14:20.200 --> 00:14:26.200
So we have a couple questions that came through. The first one is what parts of

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:31.000
the pipeline are not replaced with RStudio Connect?

00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:39.479
All of the R logic and the interactions with the database or the

00:14:39.479 --> 00:14:45.760
buckets or how we execute models. So it's yeah the things that were replaced that

00:14:45.760 --> 00:14:51.119
might be easier to answer. So we replaced Jenkins and the monitoring and the

00:14:51.119 --> 00:14:56.000
dashboarding with all of the capabilities of RStudio Connect.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:00.840
Another question from Glenn. How do you handle shiny dashboards that require

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:08.280
querying large amounts of data that take considerable time? So we do use, we do

00:15:08.280 --> 00:15:14.400
cast the data. So if there has been a more recent run within the same day or

00:15:14.400 --> 00:15:21.359
within the same whatever period we want to update the dashboard in, it's faster

00:15:21.359 --> 00:15:25.760
if it's not the first time because we use the cast data. If it's the first

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:31.880
run and the query time is quite long then the dashboard will take quite a

00:15:31.880 --> 00:15:37.760
long time to load. And one last question. So is there something intrinsic to use

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:44.119
RStudio Connect that motivated the switch from S3 to the Google Cloud, well

00:15:44.119 --> 00:15:50.559
GCS? No, so the move between Amazon and Google was completely coming from our

00:15:50.559 --> 00:15:54.640
data platforms team because I think there are packages to interact both with

00:15:54.640 --> 00:16:00.440
AWS or GCS. We should have time for one last one. So what type of

00:16:00.440 --> 00:16:06.840
challenges have you had with scheduling jobs in Connect? I don't think we had any

00:16:06.840 --> 00:16:13.880
issues with scheduling on a time schedule. One thing we would really

00:16:13.880 --> 00:16:20.880
really like to have is to have trigger based runs of models. So if

00:16:20.880 --> 00:16:25.359
we could have some rules under which the model would run instead of just

00:16:25.359 --> 00:16:30.719
specifying that the job needs to run every hour or every day, to have maybe

00:16:30.719 --> 00:16:35.200
another job to go in BigQuery, check a field, if the field had changed then run

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:40.719
the model. Does that make sense? Thank you.

